Copyright.AdditionalInfo: Following the successful conclusion of the EarthScope program in 2018, magnetotelluric (MT) coverage of the United States continues under a grant from NASA. This dataset is intended to flow seamlessly with the 2006-2018 EarthScope USArray MT dataset, using the same nominal 70 km station spacing and the same set of data frequencies. MT stations are deployed as a rolling array of approximately 20 instruments that are each allowed to record for two to three weeks and then relocated to a new station. Under EarthScope, MT data covered the northern tier of the United States, from the Pacific Northwest to New England, as well as the southeastern part of the country. Magnetic and electric time-series data are processed into MT transfer functions (impedance tensors and vertical magnetic transfer functions). Information on the EarthScope USArray MT Array project can be found at http://www.usarray.org/researchers/obs/magnetotelluric. These data have been essential in large-scale tectonic studies of North America. The dataset has been the foundation of significant publications on the Pacific Northwest, the Midcontinent Rift, and the ancient accretion of North America. It has also proven to be very valuable in showing vulnerabilities to the power grid by offering a means to predict potentially damaging electric fields in the ground induced by geomagnetic activity. One change from previous years is the data quality rating. As before, data are given a quality rating from 1 to 5, with 5 being the highest quality. Transfer function data collected under EarthScope were only made available on the SPUD web interface if it was judged by Oregon State University's team to be of quality 3 or greater. Now, however, the best transfer functions from all stations will be available even if they are assigned a rating of 1 or 2. A quality rating of 1 indicates that little or no usable data was collected at that location and a rating of 2 indicates that data should be usable at some frequencies but overall does not meet our standards for MT inversion. We recognize that while low-quality transfer MT functions may be of minimal use for inversion, the information may be helpful to users who wish to use electromagnetic data for other purposes or to identify locations where it may be difficult for future researchers to obtain high-quality data. The MT instruments are operated and maintained by the National Geoelectromagnetic Facility at Oregon State University under a subaward (PI Adam Schultz) from IRIS.
